decision_style|evidence|Evidence|Evidence|Looks for facts, data, proof, observed patterns, and what can be known before committing.|1|true|draft|You anchor decisions in what can be demonstrated and tested.|Keep distinct from principle by focusing on what is known, not what should be true.
decision_style|instinct|Instinct|Instinct|Uses judgement, experience, pattern recognition, and felt sense when data is incomplete.|2|true|draft|You use experienced pattern-recognition to move when certainty is incomplete.|Keep distinct from evidence by avoiding proof language.
decision_style|principle|Principle|Principle|Tests decisions against standards, obligations, values, and what should remain true under pressure.|3|true|draft|You protect standards and obligations so pressure does not erode what matters.|Keep distinct from pragmatism by centering non-negotiables and commitments.
decision_style|pragmatism|Pragmatism|Pragmatism|Narrows toward what will work, what can be executed, and what moves the situation forward.|4|true|draft|You move decisions toward executable progress and workable outcomes.|Keep distinct from instinct by focusing on implementability and operational movement.
